                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400106-name-124" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-124" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-124" type="surname" value="GARNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-124" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH GARNER.</persName>
                  </hi>I am wife of John Garner, who keeps the Half Moon public-house, Strutton-ground, Westminster. These four pots are his—the prisoner was an occasional customer—he goes about with hearth<lb></lb>stones—he was at our house on the 27th of December—he had some porter or some spirits, and went away between ten and eleven o'clock—the policeman brought the pots to me afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400106-name-125" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-125" type="surname" value="COOKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400106-name-125" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>FRANCIS COOKE</persName>
                  </hi>(<hi rend="italic">police-constable B</hi>37.) I fell in with the prisoner in Snow's-rents, about a quarter-past eleven o'clock that night—I saw hit pocket bulky—I stopped him, and asked what he had got—he said "Nothing"—I put my hand into his pocket, and found a quart pot and a pint pot—I asked how he came by them—he would not give me a satisfac<lb></lb>tory answer—I took him to the station-house, and found the other pots and the owner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner</hi>. It is my first offence—I always work hard for my living.</p>
